## Introduction

**.NET MAUI mobile and desktop applications that want to call cloud-based Large Language Models (LLMs)** face a fundamental challenge: *the client app cannot be fully trusted*. If a mobile app communicates directly with an AI service (like Azure OpenAI or OpenAIs API), any secret API keys or system prompts included in the app can be extracted by a malicious user or abused through tampering with requests. Attackers could decompile the app to steal API keys, modify the conversation context (injecting malicious system messages), or manipulate tool definitions and conversation history for unintended actions. This can result in serious issues: from *unauthorized API usage that racks up costs* to *prompt injection attacks that exfiltrate data or subvert the AIs instructions*. [\[backmesh.com\]](https://backmesh.com/blog/openai-api-mistakes/), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

To mitigate these risks while still delivering rich AI features on mobile/desktop, **the recommended solution is to introduce a secure proxy (a trusted backend server)** between the MAUI client and the AI model service. This proxy acts as a **backend-for-frontend (BFF)** that owns the API keys and strictly mediates all communication, ensuring the client can never directly manipulate the AI agent beyond approved inputs. The proxy can sanitize and validate what the client sends and receives, enforce usage policies, and integrate additional safety layers (like rate limiting or content moderation) before relaying queries to the actual AI service. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

In this report, we **analyze a spectrum of proxy architectures**  from simple passthrough gateways to full-fledged server-side agents  and discuss how each addresses (or fails to address) security threats. We compare to **real-world practices** (e.g. how ChatGPTs official app, Microsoft Copilot, or Googles AI apps handle this problem) and examine how solutions integrate with the **Microsoft.Extensions.AI (MEAI)** model of using `IChatClient` for unified AI access. We assess the **Microsoft Agent-User Interaction (AG-UI) protocol** as a potential foundation for building secure, feature-rich agent communication. We also explore strategies for **safe on-device tool execution**, developer experience considerations, and future or novel approaches (like **protocol negotiation**, **WASM sandboxes**, **Trusted Execution Environments**, or emerging standards like **Model Context Protocol (MCP)**).

The goal is to provide a **comprehensive, technically deep comparison** of secure proxy patterns for MAUI + AI apps, addressing the key question: *What is the best architecture for a secure proxy that balances robust security with developer convenience and the flexibility of MEAI?*

***

## Proxy Architecture Spectrum: From Thin to Thick

Modern AI-enabled mobile applications can use a variety of proxy architectures to connect to cloud AI services. These approaches can be visualized on a spectrum from **thin proxies** (minimal server logic, mostly forwarding requests) to **thick proxies** (server takes full control of the AI interaction). Each point on this spectrum trades off **ease of implementation vs. security & control**.

**Figure 1** below outlines representative architecture patterns along this spectrum, highlighting key differences.

### 1. **Simple Passthrough Proxy**  *Dumb Pipe*

A **passthrough proxy** acts as a minimal relay. The MAUI app sends requests in a standard OpenAI format (or Azure OpenAI format) to a lightweight server endpoint, which simply **attaches the real API key or credentials and forwards the request** to the actual AI service. The response (including streaming tokens) is then proxied back to the client. The client can use the familiar `IChatClient` interface in Microsoft.Extensions.AI, just pointing it to the proxys URL instead of directly to the OpenAI endpoint. [\[backmesh.com\]](https://backmesh.com/blog/openai-api-mistakes/)

*   **Advantages:** Easiest to implement. The client and server can both use out-of-the-box OpenAI or Azure OpenAI SDKs: the server just wraps one extra hop to hide credentials. Streaming works natively  the proxy can forward data as it arrives, preserving the real-time user experience. This transparency means minimal modifications to how the MAUI app is coded; developers still compose prompts and call `CompleteAsync` or `CompleteStreamingAsync` on the `IChatClient` as usual. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

*   **Limitations:** Security is **minimal**. While the API key isnt directly in the binary, any determined attacker can intercept the clients calls or decompile the app to find the proxys address and *its authentication method (if any)*. If the proxy isnt locked down, an attacker could call it directly and use the companys AI key arbitrarily. Also, since the proxy just forwards requests, the **client retains full control** over the conversation  a malicious or compromised client can still inject system-level instructions, define fake tools, or send excessively large prompts, because the proxy isnt examining or altering the payload. Essentially, a passthrough proxy solves *only one* problem (hiding the raw API key) while leaving other vector points (prompt injection, overuse, content safety, etc.) unaddressed. This approach might suffice for quick prototypes or internal demos, but **it is not recommended for production apps** that run on untrusted devices. [\[backmesh.com\]](https://backmesh.com/blog/openai-api-mistakes/) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

### 2. **Basic Intercepting Proxy**  *Sanitize & Forward*

An **intercepting proxy** goes a step further: the server still relays standard AI API calls, but **inspects and modifies requests and responses in transit**. The client uses `IChatClient` normally, but the proxys code can enforce certain rules:

*   **Strip or override system prompts:** For example, the proxy might *ignore any system messages from the client* and instead inject its own vetted system prompt (establishing consistent agent instructions). This thwarts basic *system message injection* attacks where a malicious client tries to manipulate the AI by slipping in a high-priority instruction. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)
*   **Enforce max tokens & rate limits:** The proxy can reject or truncate requests that exceed allowed prompt lengths or token counts, preventing abuse that could cause excessive charges or denial-of-service to your API quota. This guards against a rogue client sending overly large prompts or rapid-fire requests. [\[backmesh.com\]](https://backmesh.com/blog/openai-api-mistakes/), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)
*   **Basic content filtering:** The proxy can integrate content moderation APIs (like OpenAIs Moderation or **Azure AI Content Safety**) to scan user inputs (and possibly model outputs) for disallowed content before forwarding. This helps catch obvious malicious or policy-violating content early. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)
*   **Remove/limit tool definitions:** If using OpenAI function calling through MEAI, the proxy can strip out any *unexpected function (tool) definitions or calls* from the users request and maintain a whitelist of allowed tools on the server side. This mitigates *client-side tool injection* where a malicious app registers a fake tool or manipulates tool descriptions to influence the model. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

Overall, a basic intercepting proxy still allows the client to use a generic chat interface (no need to hardcode domain-specific endpoints), but **the server now actively **polices** the conversation**. Its a **middle-ground** approach: *higher security than a dumb relay*, but still relatively easy to implement within the MEAI ecosystem. For example, a .NET developer could use a simple ASP.NET Core Web API with an `HttpClient` or `OpenAIClient` to forward requests. They might add an HTTP pipeline or Azure API Management policies to perform tasks like header/token validation, prompt length checks, and content scanning. [\[backmesh.com\]](https://backmesh.com/blog/openai-api-mistakes/), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

*   **Key tension:** How much can the proxy clean up or constrain requests *without breaking the apps intended functionality*? If the app legitimately needs to set certain system messages or pass custom tool definitions, a naive proxy that strips anything unknown could hinder valid use cases. The server has limited understanding of *why* the clients prompt looks the way it does, so it must tread carefully  for example, removing certain content might distort the conversation. The challenge is to enforce **safety and policy compliance** while maintaining the **flexibility of an open prompt-based interface**.

### 3. **Schema-Validated or **Contract** Proxy**

This approach strengthens the intercepting proxy by establishing a **predefined contract or schema** for the AI conversation. The idea is to precisely define what kinds of messages, tools, or formats the client is allowed to send, and have the server validate all incoming requests against this contract before forwarding. If a request deviates from the expected format or content, the proxy rejects or sanitizes it.

*   **How it works:** The development team would design a **conversation schema** or policy  for instance, specifying which tools (functions) can be called, what roles messages can have, acceptable value ranges for parameters, and perhaps a conversation flow (e.g., user messages must alternate with assistant responses, etc.). The proxy would implement checks to enforce this. This could be done via custom code or even configuration-based rules (for example, API gateways allow defining JSON schema validation policies for requests).

*   **Benefits:** *Security is stronger.* The server treats the clients input as data to be validated rather than full agent instructions. For example, if the schema says the client can only provide a user message in plain text and optionally a location coordinate, then any attempt by the client to include a system or assistant message, or define a new tool, would be caught and blocked. This mitigates **message list injections, state/context injections, and tool injections** by strictly limiting what shapes of input the client can send. The server can also enforce **response schemas**: e.g., requiring the AIs answer to be in a specific JSON format or disallowing it from calling unapproved tools, which helps ensure *predictable output* and prevents misuse of tools. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

*   **Challenges:** The main difficulty is that you must **design and maintain this contract**. It introduces a layer of complexity  essentially youre formalizing the conversation structure in a way both client and server must agree on. The client and server need to stay in sync with the contract version; updates must be carefully managed to avoid breaking compatibility. If the contract is too strict, it may stifle new features or require frequent updates. If its too loose, you lose the security benefits. Its essentially a custom protocol superimposed on top of the LLMs interface, which is powerful but requires more up-front design work and possible limitations on using new LLM features unless theyre accounted for in the schema.

*   **Example:** A real-world analog is the concept of **API schema validation** in API gateways or GraphQL. In fact, one could imagine using a **GraphQL layer** as a contract-driven proxy: the client calls a GraphQL API that internally translates to an LLM prompt. The GraphQL schema dictates exactly what queries are allowed. Some companies have explored such patterns to structure AI interactions, though this tends to work best for *well-defined tasks* (e.g., filling forms, retrieving info) rather than free-form chat.

### 4. **Domain-Specific Backend (REST/RPC)**  *Server-Owned Prompts*

On the far end of the spectrum, the client relinquishes control of the conversation format entirely. Instead of the MAUI app calling a generic chat completion API, it calls **custom REST or RPC endpoints** (or uses method-specific remote procedure calls) that encapsulate the AIs behavior. In this model, the **server fully owns the prompt engineering and tool selection** for each operation. The client might invoke an endpoint like `POST /SummarizeDocument` or `POST /PlanTrip` with structured inputs (e.g. a document to summarize, or trip parameters), and the server internally crafts the prompt, possibly calls the LLM and various tools, and returns a final result.

*   **Advantages:** *Maximum security & control.* The client no longer passes arbitrary prompts or tool definitions at all  those are handled by the trusted server. This virtually eliminates the risk of prompt or tool injection by a malicious client, since the client isnt providing the full message list; its just providing small, *constrained inputs* (like the users query text or form fields). The server can use rigorous logic to build prompts from these inputs, insert its own system messages, and ignore any user-specified instructions that might be harmful. It can also fully log and monitor AI usage, apply business-specific filters, and ensure no data leaks to the client except whats intended. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

*   **Drawbacks:** The **developer experience shifts**  you *dont use `IChatClient` on the client at all* in this scenario. Instead, the MAUI app is calling custom web endpoints that you implement. This means losing the generic, model-agnostic programming model of MEAI on the client side. Also, any change in AI behavior typically requires a server deployment (e.g. adding a new AI feature means building a new endpoint or updating the servers prompt logic). Its more akin to a traditional web API development cycle. Additionally, *on-device tool usage is basically impossible* in this model unless you implement specific API calls for those device functions  which again means more manual work and less flexibility.

*   **Use cases:** A server-owned approach is common in **high-security or enterprise scenarios** where dynamic prompts are too risky. For example, the official **ChatGPT mobile app** and Microsofts various Copilot features almost certainly follow this pattern: the client apps do not construct arbitrary open-ended prompts or hold any secret keys. Instead, they send user input to a *first-party backend service* (OpenAIs or Microsofts servers) which then adds all the system prompts and context and calls the LLM behind the scenes. The client gets a safe response to display, and any additional UI features (like citations, tool actions, etc.) are orchestrated by the server. This is effectively the **trusted frontend server** pattern strongly recommended by Microsoft for AG-UI and similar agent frameworks. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

### 5. **AG-UI Protocol (Agent-User Interaction)**  *Full-Fidelity Agent Proxy*

Between the extremes of a raw LLM API and a completely custom backend, there exists a specialized solution: the **AG-UI protocol** developed by Microsofts **Agent Framework**. AG-UI is an **open, event-driven protocol** designed specifically to connect front-end applications (including mobile apps) with AI *agents* running on a backend. It encompasses advanced features like bidirectional streaming, **frontend and backend tool use**, shared conversational state, and UI synchronization. In the .NET ecosystem, the Agent Framework provides: [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf), [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)

*   **Server components** (e.g. an `AGUI` ASP.NET Core middleware via `MapAGUI()` or similar) to easily create an HTTP + SSE endpoint for an agent.
*   **Client libraries** (`Microsoft.Agents.AI.AGUI` in .NET, or JS client in CopilotKit) that implement the `IChatClient` interface by speaking AG-UI over HTTP/SSE. For MAUI developers, this means you can treat the remote AI as an `IChatClient` instance (just like an OpenAI client), but under the hood its using the AG-UI protocol to communicate with the agent server. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.agents.ai.agui.aguichatclient?view=agent-framework-dotnet-latest)

**How it works:** In AG-UI, the conversation is not a single request/response; its a **continuous event stream**. The client opens a connection (HTTP request kept alive, typically using **Server-Sent Events** for streaming) and sends a *user message event* to the server to start the conversation. The server (the agent) then processes it, possibly invokes *tools* (which could be on the server side or instruct the client to execute a *frontend tool* like accessing the camera), and streams back events such as partial *assistant responses* or *tool requests*. The protocol includes rich metadata for things like naming and describing tools, handling *function call results*, and even supporting a *human in the loop* where the server can ask the client to clarify something or to approve an action. Its essentially an extension of the typical LLM conversation to a **full agent loop** that can interact with both cloud services (backend tools) and device capabilities (frontend tools) in a standardized way. [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf) [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf), [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)

*   **Pros:** AG-UI offers a ready-made solution for many problems wed otherwise have to solve ourselves. It inherently separates user-level input from system-level instructions: the agents system prompt and toolset are defined on the server side, not by the client. The client can only send user messages (and user-triggered tool results) unless explicitly allowed to do more. This aligns with the security best practice of a *trusted mediator server*. AG-UI also elegantly handles streaming via SSE (with built-in support in .NET 10 and libraries) and can maintain conversation state over a long-lived session without the client resending the entire history each turn (the server tracks state). It even supports *frontend tool execution*  for example, the server can send an event like ToolCallStart for a `get_location` tool, and the AG-UI client on MAUI will invoke a pre-registered handler to get the device GPS coordinates, then automatically return a ToolResult event to the server. This is a powerful model: the client can safely provide device-specific capabilities to the agent **without exposing the actual tool logic to the LLM** (the LLM just sees the results). [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations) [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)

*   **Cons:** Despite its rich feature set, AG-UI is *not a turnkey security solution by itself*. The **AG-UI documentation strongly warns** that you should ***never expose an AG-UI server directly to an untrusted client*** without a mediating layer. In other words, if you simply stood up an AG-UI endpoint and let the MAUI app connect, youd be back to square one regarding trust: a hacked client could send malicious events (fake tool responses, injected system messages, etc.) and subvert the agent. The onus is still on developers to implement **authentication, input validation, and policy enforcement** on the server side. Unfortunately, as of early 2026, the Agent Frameworks provided components are focused on functionality, not security  theres no built-in auth or rate limiting. Youd need to integrate your own mechanisms (e.g., OAuth tokens, input sanitization callbacks, content filters) with the AG-UI server endpoints. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

*   **Maturity and Overhead:** The AG-UI .NET library is currently marked as **preview** (e.g. version `1.0.0-preview` in packages), implying potential breaking changes. Its also fairly **heavyweight**; by one estimate, using the Agent Framework could introduce on the order of dozens of new NuGet package dependencies, since AG-UI is part of a larger ecosystem of agent support libraries (planning, memory, etc.). The overall **binary size and memory impact** on a mobile app has not been fully documented yet, and for some developers this complexity might be overkill if they just need a simple chat with one or two tools. There is also the question of *protocol versioning*: because AG-UI is evolving (and has overlaps with other emerging standards like MCP and A2A), an app and server built today might need updates if the protocol changes. Ideally, the AG-UI client and server libraries handle version negotiation, but caution is warranted when adopting a pre-1.0 technology for production. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.agents.ai.agui.aguichatclient?view=agent-framework-dotnet-latest) [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)

*   **Use cases:** AG-UI shines for **complex, interactive agents** where you want to maintain a single long-running conversation with shared context and allow *both cloud-based and device-based tool use*. If you need the LLM to, say, query a database (server tool) and take a photo or check local sensors (device tool) within one conversation, AG-UI provides a structured way to do that, supported by Microsofts tooling. Its essentially the protocol behind experiences like **Copilot Chat** (on the web, in apps like Bing Chat or GitHub Copilot X) and is being positioned as a standard for **frontend-agent communications** across languages. [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf), [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)

*   **Hybrid approaches:** One could also combine AG-UI with a thin or intercepting proxy. For example, the MAUI app might run an AG-UI client, but instead of connecting directly to the actual agent server, it connects to a lightweight **AG-UI-aware proxy**. This proxy could perform additional authentication and validation on the AG-UI events (ensuring no disallowed content in user messages, etc.) before relaying them to the real agent. Such a two-tier AG-UI deployment is complex, but not inconceivable, especially for high-security scenarios. Its effectively an implementation of the trusted frontend server model referenced in the AG-UI docs  the front-tier server would create and control the AG-UI conversation on behalf of the client, only exposing a tightly constrained subset of functionality to the app. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

| **Server-Owned REST/RPC** (BFF)      |  No (`IChatClient` used **only on server** side)                                                                                                                             |  *Extra work* needed for streaming (e.g. chunked responses or WebSocket)                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 |  None (server would handle via cloud APIs instead)                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 |  **Very High**  server fully controls prompts, tools, and policies [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)          |  **Highest** (new API design + server logic for each feature)                                                                                                                                                                         |
| **AG-UI Protocol** (Agent Framework) | Yes (via `AGUIChatClient`) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.agents.ai.agui.aguichatclient?view=agent-framework-dotnet-latest) |  SSE streaming built-in [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf) |  Yes (via *frontend tool* events) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations) |  *None by default*  must add auth & validation manually [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)                                                                                                                                              |  **Medium-High** (setup Agent Framework; many features out-of-box, but new tech in preview)                                                                                                                                           |

**Key Takeaway:** *The farther right you go on this spectrum, the more the **server is in control**  improving security but also increasing complexity and potentially limiting flexibility.* Many real apps may blend aspects of these: e.g. start as a passthrough during prototyping, then evolve to an intercepting or contract-checking proxy for production, as policies firm up. The right architecture depends on the apps risk tolerance and needs:

*   **Consumer-facing apps** or those handling sensitive data (enterprise) should lean towards the *thicker, more secure* end (contract-validated or full BFF). For example, Microsoft 365 Copilot features and **the ChatGPT mobile app** use a fully server-driven approach  the client is essentially a thin UI, and all AI prompting and tool usage happens in a controlled cloud environment. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)
*   **Internal or low-risk prototypes** might start at the thinner end for speed, then progressively harden. For instance, a team could initially deploy a simple proxy to hide keys and gather usage data, but later introduce validation rules or migrate to a robust solution like API Managements AI gateway (which provides many filtering and governance features out-of-the-box). [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

Next, we will examine **security considerations** in more depth, then explore how these architectures relate to existing industry practices, MEAI integration, and other aspects.

## Security Deep-Dive: Threats, Mitigations, and Residual Risks

No matter which proxy architecture you choose, its important to design with a **zero-trust mindset** toward the client. In practice, that means assuming a malicious actor could reverse-engineer or tamper with your MAUI app, and therefore any data from the client must be **validated on the server** before being trusted. The main threat vectors for an AI-powered mobile app include: [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

*   **API Credential Exposure:** If the app contains an API key or token to contact the LLM service, an attacker can extract it (even from native binaries) and then use it directly. *Mitigation:* **Never embed secret keys in the app**. Always keep them on a secure server. Use a **proxy or secure credential service** to supply credentials when calling the AI API. In Azure, prefer **Managed Identities or Key Vault** to avoid even having secrets in app settings. The proxy should require authentication (e.g. user-specific tokens) so that a stolen API key alone cant be used by arbitrary parties. [\[backmesh.com\]](https://backmesh.com/blog/openai-api-mistakes/) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

*   \*\*User Authentication & **Auth Token Theft:** Even if the AI API key is secured on the server, the client will likely need some form of authentication (e.g., a JWT or session token to call the proxy). Attackers might steal this token (for example, by decompiling local storage or intercepting traffic) and then impersonate the user to access the AI service. *Mitigation:* Use **short-lived tokens** and **refresh mechanisms** for client authentication. Implement **token verification** on the proxy (validate signatures, expiration, and scopes on each request). Consider tying tokens to device or app instance  for instance, some systems use **device attestation** (such as SafetyNet on Android or App Attest on iOS) to ensure tokens are only usable from genuine, untampered client apps. Additionally, enforce per-user or per-token **quotas and rate limits** on the proxy, so a stolen token cant be abused beyond a certain threshold. [\[backmesh.com\]](https://backmesh.com/blog/openai-api-mistakes/), [\[backmesh.com\]](https://backmesh.com/blog/openai-api-mistakes/) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

*   **Prompt/Message Injection:** A malicious client can insert instructions in the conversation to hijack the agent. This includes **system message injection** (fake system or developer-level directives), **assistant message injection** (forging or altering the conversation history), or **context injection** (sending hidden malicious data as context or in attachments). *Mitigation:* The proxy should treat the clients messages as untrusted: [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)
    *   **Strip or fix roles:** e.g. ignore any `$role: "system"` content from the app, ensuring only *user* (and possibly *assistant* if echoing back prior responses) roles pass through. The server can manage the true system prompts and even user profiles or other context on behalf of the client. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)
    *   **Canonicalize history handling:** If the client passes conversation history, the server should verify it (e.g., require that all prior assistant messages match what the AI actually responded, using IDs or server-signed transcripts). Another approach is for the server to maintain the authoritative conversation state server-side (so the client cant fabricate or alter history) and ignore any client-supplied history beyond the last user prompt.
    *   **Limit context injection:** For features like attach a file or include this context, the server might restrict the format/size of attached data and sanitize it. If the protocol allows the client to label content as e.g. context, ensure that doesnt become a vector for hidden instructions (maybe treat all context purely as user-provided data). [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)
    *   **Validate content**: Use **content filtering** on user inputs to catch known prompt injection patterns or disallowed content. For example, Microsofts guidance for Azure OpenAI suggests using the built-in content filters or Azure Content Safety to screen prompts and completions for policy compliance. This wont catch everything but can mitigate obvious attacks (like a user asking the model to ignore all instructions). [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

*   **Function/Tool Injection & Misuse:** Advanced LLM apps often use **tool or function calling**, where the model can request to execute a function (like a web search, database query, or device capability). An untrusted client could try to register **unauthorized or manipulative tools**  e.g., a fake tool that tricks the model, or tamper with the tool outputs. The client could also simply lie about tool results (for client-side tools) or call tools without permission. *Mitigations:*
    *   **Define tools on the server.** For any critical backend tool (e.g., database access), the server should expose it to the model and decide when its called. The client should *not* be telling the model about new tools that the server isnt aware of. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)
    *   **Lock down tool specs:** If the client is allowed to declare some tools (like device-based tools under AG-UI), the server should vet the tool definitions. The **AG-UI approach** is that the client declares available tools at session start (with metadata), and then the server decides when to invoke them. The server should refuse any tool thats not pre-registered or whose schema doesnt match expected parameters. [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf), [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)
    *   **Verify tool results** when possible. For server-side tools, the server directly executes them (so results are inherently trusted). For client-side tools (like taking a photo or getting GPS location), its more challenging: one strategy is to design the protocol such that the server can *request the raw data* and even perform duplicate calculations to verify (though it cant, say, re-take a photo). In high-trust scenarios, one might employ platform-specific features  e.g., iOS and Android provide **secure enclaves and attestation services**  to ensure the data (like a sensor reading) comes from a genuine source. However, these are advanced techniques; often, the simpler mitigation is to **limit what frontend tools are allowed to do**, and to require explicit user approval for actions. For example, if the agent wants to send an email via a client tool, design the system to always require user confirmation before sending, thereby preventing silent abuse of that tool by a compromised client.
    *   **Monitor tool usage:** The proxy can maintain an audit log of all tool invocations and their inputs/outputs, helping detect anomalies. If a client is repeatedly calling a certain tool in suspicious ways, the server could flag or block that client.

*   **Overuse & Cost Exploitation:** Without checks, a malicious client could call the AI endpoint in a tight loop or ask for huge completions, leading to skyrocketing API bills or denial of service. *Mitigations:* Implement **rate limiting and quotas** per user/device on the proxy side. The MEAI `DelegatingChatClient` pipeline can include a *Throttling* handler for client-side rate limiting, but that can be bypassed by an attacker who modifies the client. Therefore, server-side rate limiting (e.g., using APIM policies or a simple in-memory counter in ASP.NET) is essential. Likewise, enforce maximum tokens per request and perhaps cumulative daily limits per user. The Azure API Management **AI gateway** offers built-in policies for token counting and quotas  for instance, a policy to cap tokens-per-minute per API key or per user ID. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

*   **Data Leakage & Response Filtering:** The LLMs responses themselves might contain sensitive data (imagine the AI leaking internal prompts or training data if tricked). Theres also a risk that a user might input confidential info and the conversation is later exposed. *Mitigation:* The proxy can perform an **output filter**  e.g., using the same content moderation API on the assistants response before relaying it. Azures guide recommends using their **Content Safety** filters on both prompts and completions as a safety net. Logs and monitoring should also be handled carefully: avoid logging entire conversations in plaintext (to prevent insider threats or breaches from exposing them), or at least apply a data retention policy where conversation logs are truncated or anonymized after some time. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities) [\[developers...openai.com\]](https://developers.openai.com/apps-sdk/guides/security-privacy), [\[developers...openai.com\]](https://developers.openai.com/apps-sdk/guides/security-privacy)

**Table 2:** *Threat mitigation by architecture.* A **full BFF** or **contract-validated proxy** provides the strongest security across the board (all major threats addressed). **Passthrough** leaves most issues unresolved (only removes the API key from the app). **Basic intercepting proxies** and **vanilla AG-UI** sit in the middle  they can address some issues (with custom logic) but have gaps unless further hardened. Notably, **AG-UI without a frontend server offers no built-in protection** against misuse; its a means of communication, not a security system. In any case, robust **authentication, validation, and monitoring** on the server side are essential in all scenarios. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)

**Defense-in-Depth:** A prudent strategy is to combine measures. For example, you might use Azure API Managements **AI gateway** features in front of your custom proxy: APIM can perform OAuth token validation, apply a *token-per-minute quota*, and run a content safety check before the request even hits your code. Then your proxy code can do deeper inspection (e.g., verify conversation state, implement business-specific policies, etc.). This layered approach ensures that even if one layer is bypassed or misconfigured, another layer mitigates damage. Microsofts guidance for Azure OpenAI emphasizes multiple layers of security, including network isolation, user authentication, and data protection measures. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

Finally, consider auditing and analytics as part of security: log unusual patterns (a spike in requests, or repeated failed attempts to use disallowed tools) and **alert or block** when they occur. Over time, these logs can also help refine your proxys rules by revealing new attack patterns. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

## Industry Prior Art: How Others Handle AI in Mobile Apps

Designing a secure AI proxy is not a theoretical exercise  major players have tackled similar challenges in their products. Here are some observations on how popular AI-powered applications handle model access from untrusted clients:

*   **OpenAIs ChatGPT Mobile App:** The official ChatGPT iOS/Android apps do *not* embed an API key; instead, users authenticate with their OpenAI accounts, and the app communicates with OpenAIs cloud service (ChatGPT backend). This is essentially a **cloud-first design**: the mobile app is a thin client (UI renderer) that sends the users query to OpenAIs servers. All chat history, system prompts, and function calls are handled server-side (within OpenAIs infrastructure), not on the device. The app likely uses a web API or websocket behind the scenes  effectively a variant of the *full backend* approach described earlier. This ensures OpenAI retains full control over the model and prompts, which is crucial for enforcing their policies and preventing misuse. The app is simply not capable of altering the agents instructions, aside from relaying the users message. **Takeaway:** *Consumer-facing AI services typically centralize the brain in the cloud.* This allows the provider to update prompts and tools on the fly and apply strict moderation. The downside is that it relies on network connectivity and cannot leverage device-specific functionality except through whatever limited channels the server chooses to expose.

*   **GitHub Copilot & Microsoft 365 Copilot (including mobile integrations):** Microsofts Copilot offerings follow a similar pattern. For instance, **GitHub Copilot** (in VS Code, which can be analogous to a desktop client) does not embed the OpenAI key; the IDE extension sends code context to GitHubs servers, which augment it with a refined prompt (including the licensed OpenAI model and additional instructions) and then call the model. Microsoft 365 Copilot (as of 2025) runs through Microsoft Graph and other cloud services even when a user invokes it in, say, the mobile Word or Outlook app. In all cases, *the heavy lifting is cloud-side*. These systems often use a **cascade of prompts/agents**: the users query might first be processed by a plan or orchestration AI agent on Microsofts side which decides whether and how to invoke the underlying LLM or other services. The client has no say in the actual prompts sent to the LLM; it only sees the end result. This multi-tier approach is partly for security and partly for reliability, as these companies can continuously update their prompt engineering and tooling logic without pushing client updates. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

*   **Googles Bard and Android Integration:** Googles conversational AI (e.g., Bard and upcoming **Gemini** model) is also served via the cloud. Even on Android devices where Google has extensive control, they havent put the full model on the device (as of 2025/2026) for general queries  instead, they send queries to Googles servers. One distinguishing factor is that Google and Apple increasingly leverage **on-device processing for certain AI features** (e.g., Apples Siri dictation and some personalizations are on-device for privacy). Googles Android and Pixel devices ship with dedicated **TPUs** (Tensor Processing Units) or the **Neural Processing Unit (NPU)**, enabling some localized ML (like image recognition or language translation) without cloud calls. However, for large-scale LLM queries or anything requiring up-to-date information, the requests still go to cloud backends. The mobile app may gather *device data* (like location, context from your calendar) to send to the cloud LLM, but it will do so via tightly controlled APIs. In Android, for example, the OS itself can mediate certain assistant requests (with user-granted permissions).

*   **Other Mobile AI Frameworks:** Outside the big players, developers often rely on similar patterns. **Firebase** and **AWS Amplify**, for instance, encourage using cloud functions or backends to wrap third-party API calls so that secrets stay on the server. Some open-source projects like **OpenAI-DotNet-Proxy** illustrate how to easily set up a .NET 8 minimal API that fronts an OpenAI API client, supporting standard auth and forwarding. Likewise, many developers use simple **reverse proxies** (NGINX, Cloudflare Workers, etc.) to add a basic safety net in front of AI APIs (caching, logging, and key protection). As AI features become more common, **API gateway products** are adding AI-specific support: for example, *Azure API Managements GenAI Gateway* provides templates to connect to OpenAI or other LLMs via a managed identity (removing the need to distribute API keys) and apply policies for input validation, output transformations, token counting, and content safety, all without writing custom code. These examples underscore that *the industry consensus is to never directly expose a raw AI model endpoint to a mobile app*. A combination of BFF patterns, API gateways, and cloud functions is used to strike the balance between user experience and control. [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/RageAgainstThePixel/OpenAI-DotNet/9-openai-dotnet-proxy) [\[backmesh.com\]](https://backmesh.com/blog/openai-api-mistakes/) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/genai-gateway-capabilities)

## Preserving the MEAI Programming Model (IChatClient) Across the Proxy

One of the design goals is to maintain the benefits of **Microsoft.Extensions.AI (MEAI)** on the client side. MAUIs integration of MEAI allows developers to use `IChatClient`  an abstraction that supports both complete responses and streaming updates, plus a pluggable middleware pipeline (via `DelegatingChatClient`) for cross-cutting concerns like logging, caching, and function/tool invocation. Ideally, using a proxy should not force developers to abandon this model or duplicate too much logic. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/ai/ichatclient), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/ai/ichatclient)

**Options for using `IChatClient` with a proxy:**

*   **Client uses `IChatClient` (with Proxy Implementation):** The simplest approach is to provide an `IChatClient` implementation that internally calls your proxy. For example, you might create a custom `ProxyChatClient` that wraps an `HttpClient`. When `GetResponseAsync` or `GetStreamingResponseAsync` is called, it translates the `ChatRequest` into an HTTP request to the proxy and streams back the result. In fact, this is exactly what the Agent Frameworks **AGUIChatClient** does: it implements `IChatClient` but instead of directly invoking an LLM, it manages an HTTP/SSE connection to the AG-UI server. A similar pattern could be applied to any proxy design  e.g., an `IChatClient` that calls a REST endpoint on your server. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.agents.ai.agui.aguichatclient?view=agent-framework-dotnet-latest)

*   **Split client/server pipeline responsibilities:** MEAIs design allows **chaining multiple `IChatClient` handlers**. In a proxy scenario, we can decide which parts of the pipeline run on the client vs on the server:
    *   The **client-side pipeline** might handle *UX-related concerns*  e.g., the `BufferedChatClient` (which smooths the streaming of tokens for better UI rendering in the MAUI app) or local caching of recent answers for offline viewing.
    *   The **server-side pipeline** would handle *critical or privileged concerns*  e.g., the actual OpenAI API call, any backend tools (database queries, web searches), and final decision-making. The server can also use MEAIs middleware: for instance, it can employ `FunctionInvokingChatClient` to automatically execute function calls using *server-side functions* (like fetching from an API) without the clients involvement.
        This separation improves security. **Example:** The MAUI sample app includes a `NonFunctionInvokingChatClient` in the client pipeline  its purpose is to prevent the client from auto-invoking functions if the server is already handling function calls, thereby avoiding double execution of tools. In general, if the server will process all function calls, the client should be configured in a no-op mode for function execution (essentially treating function call responses as just another message to forward). Conversely, if you want the client to execute some functions (like device tools), then the servers LLM should output a tool request that the client recognizes  the division of labor must be carefully architected.

*   **Maintaining conversation history:** MEAI expects the developer (or the `IChatClient`) to manage the conversation messages. With a stateless proxy, one could have the client send the full message list on each request (this is how OpenAIs API works by default), and `IChatClient` can help accumulate and resend previous messages. However, from a security standpoint, a stateful server is safer: the server can keep track of the conversation history associated with a session or user and ensure it cant be manipulated. With a stateful design, the client can just send the latest user message with a conversation ID, and the server will retrieve prior messages from its store (or cache). This prevents a compromised client from dropping or altering earlier messages to change context. If using AG-UI, the protocol inherently maintains state on the server as part of the agent session, so the `AGUIChatClient` on MAUI doesnt need to resend old messages each time  it just sends new events and receives updates. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/ai/ichatclient)

*   **Serializing requests:** Standard OpenAI API requests (which MEAI uses under the hood for its default `OpenAIChatClient`) are JSON with a list of messages. These translate naturally over HTTP. However, if your proxy uses a more complex protocol (like streaming or binary gRPC), you might need to adjust the `ProxyChatClient` implementation. For example, a gRPC-based proxy could use an `IAsyncEnumerable<ChatResponse>` for streaming, which still fits in the `IChatClient` asynchronous streaming model. The key is ensuring your proxys communication pattern aligns with the `IChatClient` interface (which expects either a single final `ChatResponse` or a stream of `ChatResponseUpdate` objects). Microsofts own implementation of streaming uses `IAsyncEnumerable<ChatResponseUpdate>` to feed tokens back to the MAUI app incrementally. So, your proxy should ideally offer a similar streaming interface. This can be done with Server-Sent Events (which is effectively how OpenAIs streaming works over HTTP) or with WebSockets or gRPC streams  each can be made to push incremental updates. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/ai/ichatclient)

*   **Ensuring consistency of middleware:** If both the client and server use MEAI pipelines, avoid duplicating responsibilities. For instance, you wouldnt want *both* client and server attempting to call functions. Likewise, if the server handles caching of responses (say, to avoid repeated calls to the LLM for identical prompts), you might disable client-side caching to prevent confusion.

In short, it is feasible to preserve a seamless MEAI experience on the client while still using a secure proxy. This typically means implementing a custom `IChatClient` on the client that delegates to the server. The MAUI team could provide this as a built-in **RemoteChatClient** for common scenarios. The server, on the other hand, could use the existing **MEAI** infrastructure and even the same `IChatClient` interface (since it can call Azure OpenAI or other models via MEAIs `OpenAIChatClient` or `AzureOpenAIChatClient` internally). By using `IChatClient` on the server, developers benefit from MEAI features (like a consistent way to configure prompts, tools, and caching) while the client side remains decoupled from model-specific code. This alignment is important: it means that much of the application logic (prompt construction, response parsing) can live on the server where its secured, yet the client UI code remains relatively simple and uses familiar abstractions to send messages and receive responses.

**The ideal distribution** may be: *lightweight UI/experience middleware on the device, heavy AI logic and policy enforcement on the server*. For example, you might run the `BufferedChatClient` (for UI responsiveness) on MAUI, with a `ProxyChatClient` that sends to your server. The server might chain an `OpenAIChatClient` (to call the model) with a `FunctionInvokingChatClient` (to execute any back-end tools) and a custom `ContentFilteringChatClient` (to sanitize outputs). This way, the overall pipeline is split across the client and server meaningfully, and you still program against `IChatClient` on both ends. Such separation of concerns maintains the **developer experience** of MEAIs composable pipeline while achieving security by relocating sensitive parts to the cloud.

## Evaluating AG-UI as a Foundation

As discussed, the **AG-UI protocol** is a notable approach because it was designed to solve exactly the problem of connecting frontends to AI agents. It originated from Microsofts **Copilot stack (Project CopilotChat/CopilotKit)** and evolved into an open standard with multiple implementations. Here we evaluate AG-UIs suitability as the foundation for a MAUI secure proxy architecture. [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)

###  Feature Richness and Flexibility

AG-UI covers several advanced needs out-of-the-box:

*   **Full-duplex Streaming:** Clients receive token streams via SSE and can also send user events or tool results asynchronously mid-conversation. [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)
*   **Frontend Tools:** The protocol formalizes how a server can ask the client to execute a device-side tool and return results. This is powerful for integrating mobile capabilities (camera, location, etc.) safely  the LLM never sees the underlying mechanism or gets direct access; it just sees the result as if a function was called. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations)
*   **Shared State & Context:** AG-UI lets the server maintain a **persistent state** (arbitrary JSON) that both client and server can update. This can model, say, an evolving scratchpad of variables or a multi-step form. It also supports *predictive state updates* to optimistically update the UI. While not every app needs this, it can enable sophisticated experiences (e.g., the AI agent filling parts of a form in the UI as it gathers info).
*   **Multi-modal and UI control:** The protocol is designed to handle images, text, and other content. It even supports UI hints (the generative UI concept) where the agent can suggest UI elements to render. This is beyond our current scope but shows the protocols flexibility for future interactive AI scenarios.

In essence, using AG-UI is like adopting a **standard language for AI frontends**. This could future-proof the app to work with different backends or integrate with other systems speaking the same protocol. It also spares the MAUI team from reinventing mechanisms for things like streaming, tool invocation, etc., since the framework provides it.

###  Security and Complexity Concerns

However, AG-UIs **weak point is security**. As noted earlier, AG-UI on its own doesnt solve the trust issue; it assumes either the client is trusted or that you add a separate trust layer. So if we embrace AG-UI, we still need to implement **all the same security measures** at the server (and possibly an extra front server) to validate inputs, authorize users, and rate limit usage. The AG-UI spec creators explicitly list all the injection and manipulation attacks possible if a malicious client speaks the protocol to your server. The *advantage* is that AG-UI gives us a structured way to intercept those  e.g., we know exactly what format a tool invocation event looks like, so a proxy can detect if a client tries to send a fake tool result or an unexpected system message and reject it. But designing and testing those validations might be non-trivial. The research literature on AG-UI also flags **security and scalability as challenges** to overcome as the protocol matures, suggesting future work on encryption and rigorous testing. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/agent-framework/integrations/ag-ui/security-considerations) [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)

Theres also the question of **operational complexity**. The Agent Framework (which implements AG-UI) is a collection of roughly two dozen NuGet packages spanning not just transport but also planning, memory management, storage, etc. Pulling in this framework could add **footprint to the client app** (if the client needs the AG-UI client library) and definitely adds moving parts to the server. Developers need to become familiar with the agent programming model (which is a bit different from a straightforward request/response style). If an app only needs a simple chat or a few tools, this might be too much indirection.

AG-UI is also a **moving target**. Its being actively developed (pre-release status as of writing) and might see breaking changes as it integrates feedback and aligns with adjacent standards (theres ongoing discussion about how it intersects or coexists with **MCP** for tool usage and with other protocols). Relying on a pre-release protocol means you should be prepared for updates. One mitigation is that, because AG-UI is an open standard with multi-language support, it may stabilize as more adopters (like web frameworks via CopilotKit, or Python libraries) rely on it. Still, a MAUI app using AG-UI needs a strategy for versioning  e.g., if the AG-UI server is updated, can the client negotiate protocol versions or does the app itself need an update? These are considerations to track as the tech evolves. [\[researchgate.net\]](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Paul-Pajo/publication/391692988_AG-UI_Enabling_User-Facing_AI_Agents_Through_a_Lightweight_Event-Based_Protocol_for_Backend-Frontend_Integration/links/6822f8a6df0e3f544f541dff/AG-UI-Enabling-User-Facing-AI-Agents-Through-a-Lightweight-Event-Based-Protocol-for-Backend-Frontend-Integration.pdf)

###  Potential Extensions to AG-UI for Security

Despite these concerns, we could consider *building on AG-UI* rather than starting from scratch. The MAUI team might collaborate with the Agent Framework team to introduce **security middleware** or guidelines specifically for mobile scenarios. For example:

*   Introducing an **authentication layer in AG-UI**: define an initial handshake event to exchange an OAuth token or session ID. Ensure that no events are processed by the agent until auth is verified.
*   **Schema enforcement in AG-UI messages**: The protocol could be extended or paired with a schema (JSON Schema for events) so that clients can only send well-formed events. Possibly, a code generation approach (similar to gRPC or typed APIs) could let the client and server share an event schema, making it easier to validate.
*   **Namespaces or capabilities**: AG-UI could implement a capability negotiation where the server informs the client what its allowed to do. For instance, the server could send an allowed tools list or a scope for the session. The client library could then automatically refuse any out-of-scope event from the app (for example, stopping the app from sending an unexpected tool response event). This would reduce burden on the server to double-check every detail (some checks can be done by the client library)  though a malicious client could bypass the library, having a redundant server check is still necessary (defense in depth).

These enhancements might not yet exist, but they could make AG-UI a more robust foundation for secure mobile AI apps. In the meantime, developers using AG-UI should plan on implementing their own safeguards in the surrounding infrastructure.

## Secure On-Device Tool Execution Models

One compelling feature of AI-enhanced apps is the ability for the AI to use **on-device capabilities**  camera, microphone, GPS, contacts, local files, etc.  as *tools* during a conversation. For example, a travel assistant agent might decide to use a `get_location` tool to tailor its answer based on where the user is, or use a `take_photo` tool to let the user snap a picture of a product and then analyze it. This raises a thorny issue: **how to allow the LLM to leverage device-specific tools without trusting the client?**

The risk is that a malicious client could simulate or alter tool outputs or call tools at will:

*   A rogue app could claim I used the `get_location` tool and the user is at \[fake coordinates] even if they arent. [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/RageAgainstThePixel/OpenAI-DotNet/9-openai-dotnet-proxy)
*   It could execute a tool like `send_email` without actually getting user consent, or provide falsified results to the agent (e.g., lying about the content of a photo).

Different architectures handle this differently:

*   In a **server-owned (REST) approach**, typically *no on-device tools are allowed*. Any required data must be sent as part of the initial request or obtained via server-side services. For example, if location is needed, the client might fetch its GPS coordinates (with user permission) and include them in the request payload; the LLM never directly decides to call a tool  its encapsulated in the apps logic. This is simplest from a security standpoint (no chance of tool misuse, because the LLM cant trigger tools on its own) but less flexible.
*   In an **AG-UI or function-calling scenario**, the agent *can request tools*, and the proxy or client executes them. **Safe tool execution** can be achieved by splitting the tool list:
    *   **Backend-Only Tools:** Tools that have side effects on enterprise data or big external actions (send email, database write, purchasing something) should be implemented on the **server side**. The agent can call these functions via the secure proxy, and the proxy decides whether to execute them (and might do extra checks like permission, or content validation on parameters). The client should not have the capability to perform these actions arbitrarily  only the server does, after appropriate validation. This protects against a malicious client, because even if it sends a fabricated ToolInvocation event, the server wont execute an unknown or disallowed tool.
    *   **Frontend (Device) Tools:** These should generally be **read-only or user-scoped actions** (retrieving data from the device, capturing user input like photos, etc.) and *non-destructive*. They inherently require user consent at the OS level (camera, location services) which provides a layer of protection. The server, when requesting a frontend tool via AG-UI, can include an expectation about the format of the result (e.g., GPS coordinates or a photo file). While the server **cannot 100% verify** that the clients provided result is truthful (short of advanced measures like notarizing images or using secure hardware attestation), we can mitigate risk by limiting what these tools can do:
        *   Prefer tools that just **gather data from the device** (location, sensors, files) or perform local computation, rather than those that take irreversible actions.
        *   For any action that could have significant effects (like sending a message or purchasing something), require **explicit user confirmation** outside the agent loop. For instance, if the agent proposes making a calendar event or sending an email, the app should surface a confirmation dialog to the user and only invoke the action if approved. This ensures that even if the agent is tricked into attempting a sensitive action, the user serves as the final gatekeeper.
        *   Design tool APIs to be as **idempotent and transparent** as possible. Logging all tool uses on the server (even for frontend tools) is helpful for audit. If the agent is supposed to have done something on the device, the server can ask the client for a confirmation event (AG-UI supports a ToolResult event which can be reviewed). In extreme cases, the server might choose to *re-run* certain tools itself if possible. E.g., if a client returns a suspiciously large chunk of text for a `searchPhoneContacts` tool, the server could have a policy to discard it or run an alternative check (though it cant directly access the phones contacts, it could check formatting or length).
        *   **Sandbox the client environment:** This is more about limiting what harm a malicious client can do. Mobile OS permissions naturally sandbox apps (one app cant easily interfere with others or the OS beyond what its allowed). If your agent has a tool to, say, read a local file, ensure its limited to the apps sandbox or a user-selected file  not arbitrary file system access.
*   **Attestation and trust:** The concept of **Trusted Execution Environments (TEE)** or secure enclaves on devices might assist with trust. For example, future implementations could use a TEE to execute certain tool code or verify outputs (imagine a secure module that the agent calls into which then triggers the camera and signs the resulting image with an unforgeable token). These are still speculative and complex to implement, but potential areas of exploration as mobile hardware (like Apples Secure Enclave and Androids TrustZone) becomes more accessible to app developers for cryptographic operations. In the near term, relying on user approval and server-side caution is more practical.

**In summary**, on-device tools enhance AI applications but should be treated cautiously in untrusted environments:

*   Keep the set of client-executable tools limited and non-destructive.
*   Have the server govern when and how those tools are called (the client shouldnt decide to run them on its own without the agents request).
*   Always require users explicit consent for any action that could affect user data or cost money.
*   Log and, if possible, double-check tool outputs.

By following these principles, we approximate a **progressive trust** model: the agent can leverage device functionality in a controlled manner, starting from safer operations (sensors, retrieve-only actions) and escalating to riskier actions only with additional safeguards.

***

## Conversation State Management: Client vs Server

Managing the conversations state (the history of messages, context, and parameters) is another crucial aspect of the architecture, with implications for both security and user experience.

There are two broad models:

*   **Client-managed state (stateless server):** The simplest implementation is for the client to send the entire conversation history with each request, so the server is essentially stateless. This is how the OpenAI API works  every chat completion call includes all prior messages as input. An `IChatClient` on the app can handle this by accumulating messages locally and sending them each time. The advantage here is simplicity  the server doesnt need to store session data. But the downsides include larger payloads (which can hurt performance on mobile networks) and, critically, the security risk that a malicious client could alter or fabricate the history. The server has to trust that the user and assistant messages it receives are an accurate reflection of the conversation. While one could mitigate tampering by, say, having the server sign its own responses (and the client return those signatures for verification), this gets complicated and still doesnt cover client-sent user messages. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/ai/ichatclient)

*   **Server-managed state (stateful server):** In a more secure setup, the server keeps track of the conversation. The client might initiate a session (obtaining a session ID or using its auth token as an identifier), and then on each new user query, the client only sends the *new question/input*, not the entire history. The server then reconstructs the full prompt by fetching the stored conversation and adding the new question. This ensures integrity: because the server stored all previous turns (which it had generated or vetted), the client cannot alter them. AG-UI essentially mandates a stateful server  the agent retains the conversation context in memory or persistent storage as the dialogue progresses. If the client were to disconnect and reconnect, it would resume the session via a token or conversation ID rather than re-upload all prior messages. This approach improves security and can reduce bandwidth usage, at the cost of more complex server logic (state storage, timeouts or cleanup for stale sessions, etc.).

**Hybrid approach:** Some systems use a **token-based history mechanism**. For example, the server could return a *conversation token* after each turn that is a cryptographic representation of the conversation state. The client returns this token with the next request, and the server validates it and maps it back to state (or even encodes the state within the token, if its short). This is akin to a stateless auth token (JWT) in web apps  it proves the conversation state wasnt tampered with by the client. This technique requires careful design (especially if the state is large, youd use a secure reference rather than encode it all in a token), but its another way to ensure integrity without storing everything server-side.

From a **privacy and compliance** standpoint, server-side state has ramifications: the server is effectively logging the conversation. In enterprise scenarios, this might be acceptable or even desired (for audit), but it triggers questions of data retention and GDPR compliance. If user data is sensitive, you must ensure the conversation store is protected and possibly ephemeral. If possible, limit what you actually store  e.g., you might avoid storing raw image data from a camera tool, and instead just store that it was used, or a reference to a secure blob storage.

For **developer experience**, stateful vs stateless also matters:

*   Stateless simplifies the server (no database needed for conversation records), but pushes the burden to the client and increases data transfer. It also complicates advanced features like shared state or long-running agents.
*   Stateful requires more infrastructure (databases or memory caches), but aligns with advanced protocols like AG-UI and allows your server to enforce consistency.

In practice, many developers opt for a hybrid: short-term state in memory or cache for active sessions (to manage turn-taking and verification), possibly with an **expiration** (e.g., clear it if the user has been idle for some time), combined with logging to a secure store for longer-term records (with appropriate privacy controls). The approach should be tailored to the apps needs and the threat model.
